li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This response provides </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘top-line’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">messages in response to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Environmental Audit Select Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inquiry.  A more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">detailed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">response is being prepared for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Department for Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs’ (Defra)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consultation on Biodiversity Offsetting in England.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">NERC is encouraged by the consultation and the information provided in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> “Biodiversity offsetting in England” Green</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> dated September 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and recognises the value of integrating concepts of ‘biodiversity’ into the planning process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his process could have a mechanism of environmental compensation at a time when developmental pressures are high. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are many issues surrounding the challenge of offsetting that are out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the scope of NERC-led research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e hope the wider consultation process will pick up these issues. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For example, biodiversity offsetting is presented as a last resort in the mitigation hierarchy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">however</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> there is scope for it to be the preferred mechanism </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">developers to get plans approved that have significant impacts. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are scien</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-based issues regarding the “standard biodiversity metric” itself. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This assumes that such units are transferable between locations and will deliver at least the same biodiversity value as the habitat lost. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Transferability will increase as the metric gets more general, but will lose ecosystem specificity and potentially value (and accuracy) of the offset</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">metric that capture</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> community structure and composition makes it less likely that compensation could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in fact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> occur.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The metric approach advocated seems to be related to major habitat characteristics, whereas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> current management approach is focused on an Ecosystem Approach, particularly the ecosystem services elements within it. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Any metric adopted should have the capability to reflect the natural capital value of the area being sacrificed and its ability to deliver the desired range of ecosystem services, as well as the structural (habitat, species) elements of biodiversity. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is not apparent that the proposals fit this requirement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">14 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>